<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10042b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10042b">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10042b"> 42(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> claddagh ring</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>The Open Forum</b> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <mark>The Claddagh Ring.</mark> Sir,&mdash;I have been sent a copy of a letter asking for information about the Claddagh rings by a correspondent of yours <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It was not originally Irish, but was brought by the sailors of the Armada <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> These Spanish sailors married into the community, impressing them with many of their customs <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> They elected a chief, whom they called &ldquo;The King of the Claddagh,&rdquo; and on his marriage he was to present his bride with one of these beautiful rings, hailing her as &ldquo;The Queen of the Claddagh.&rdquo; It subsequently became permitted for other women of the community to wear this pattern of ring as wedding ring on the fore finger of the right hand until now, when it is a general custom. <small> <a name="CT12apr24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CT12apr24"><cite title="source">Connacht Tribune</cite></a> (12 April 1924) 7/5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01018j" href="c01all.htm#c01018j">VI.C.01:018(j)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
